pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 438635182, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
if ENV["HOMEBREW_SORBET"]
  gem "sorbet"
  gem "sorbet-runtime"
end
```

Might be nice to do this and leave the `Gemfile.lock` and others as-is until we have code that's going to be used by more users. Thoughts? Does that work as expected for you?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 11, 8, 45, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 438668414, 'comment_body': 'If we're going to go with using Sorbet - which we are, otherwise we wouldn't have a GSoC project for it - then I'd be inclined to make this as normal as possible as early as possible so we have less to unpick to make this mainstream later.

Incremental is good, but I thought that meant "only enabling it everywhere slowly, and on CI at the very end", etc.

That said, keeping it behind an envvar does restrict it to people who want it (that is: Vidushee, us) and might discourage enthusiastic contributors from seeing Sorbet in the Gemfile, running `srb tc` and doing the work themselves. But I don't know how many people would actually do that - the PRs do have labels on, after all.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 11, 9, 45, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 438685426, 'comment_body': "> If we're going to go with using Sorbet - which we are, otherwise we wouldn't have a GSoC project for it - then I'd be inclined to make this as normal as possible as early as possible so we have less to unpick to make this mainstream later.

I agree but there's similar discussions in https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/pull/7678 and I think it's important we're being consistent. 

I think we want to keep the number of gems we're installing for contributors who want to e.g. just run `brew style` at a minimum until they are going to interact with that functionality.



> might discourage enthusiastic contributors from seeing Sorbet in the Gemfile, running `srb tc` and doing the work themselves.

I think we do want to discourage that to avoid conflicts/stepping on toes.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 11, 10, 17, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 438689166, 'comment_body': "> I agree but there's similar discussions in https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/pull/7678 and I think it's important we're being consistent.

In that case, I'm in favour of consistency as long as all projects (that touch gems) do the same.

> I think we do want to discourage that to avoid conflicts/stepping on toes.

Definitely. OK, let's do it this way (provided it works).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 11, 10, 25, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 438700311, 'comment_body': "Just checked and it works fine. I think it will be okay to keep the gemfile this way till we don't add method signatures. 👍 ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 11, 10, 49, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vidusheeamoli', 'type': 'User'}]

Sorbet was reporting errors (error code: [4010](https://sorbet.org/docs/error-reference#4010)) on the auto-generated tapioca RBI files. Since `sorbet-typed` has a good enough RBI for `json` hence we can exclude `json` from tapioca generation using the `--exclude` flag.

-----

Error 4015, was caused because Sorbet could not identify `MacOS` as a class/module. This was because `MacOS` was dynamically defined in both `os/linux.rb:30` and `os/mac.rb:15`. 

I tried to replicate the module nesting in `os/linux.rb` file as per my understanding on sorbet.run :
- [Example](https://sorbet.run/#%23%20typed%3A%20false%0Amodule%20OS%0A%20%20module%20Mac%0A%20%20%20%20%3A%3AMacOS%20%3D%20self%0A%20%20%20%20def%20self.func1%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%22hello%22%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%0A%20%20%20%20module%20Xcode%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20def%20self.func2%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%22ok%22%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20end%0Aend%0A%0Aputs%20MacOS.func1%20%23%20output%3A%20%22hello%22%0Aputs%20MacOS%3A%3AXcode.func2%20%23%20output%3A%20%22ok%22%0A) that fails
- Fixed [example](https://sorbet.run/#%23%20typed%3A%20false%0Amodule%20OS%0A%20%20module%20Mac%0A%20%20%20%20%3A%3AMacOS%20%3D%20OS%3A%3AMac%20%23%20Modified%20line%0A%20%20%20%20def%20self.func1%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%22hello%22%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%0A%20%20%20%20module%20Xcode%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20def%20self.func2%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%22ok%22%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20end%0Aend%0A%0Aputs%20MacOS.func1%20%23%20output%3A%20%22hello%22%0Aputs%20MacOS%3A%3AXcode.func2%20%23%20output%3A%20%22ok%22%0A)

[WIP] Setting `typed` to `true` for `cmd/home.rb` has introduced 10 new type errors. Prior to this, only 13 syntax related errors were being reported by Sorbet. This PR aims to resolve all of the new type errors. For now I've used very redundant fixes for the type errors. The next few days, I will be discussing more feasible workarounds with my mentors and implementing them in this draft PR.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 445170676, 'comment_body': 'Not including this line causes Sorbet to report error [7003](https://sorbet.org/docs/error-reference#7003) for the `exec_browser` method (this method is defined in `utils.rb` in the `Kernel` module)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 24, 21, 3, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vidusheeamoli', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445365787, 'comment_body': 'Hmm, again this seems like weird behaviour from Sorbet. Does an explicit `require` fix it? Kernel is already included implicitly.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 7, 40, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445442643, 'comment_body': '`require` does not help here. :/', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 9, 53, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vidusheeamoli', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445505812, 'comment_body': "The behaviour is because it tries to consider how modules can be mixins.

Basically the inheritance by default goes:

```
Class/Module -> Object -> BasicObject
```

Ruby by default has `include Kernel` in `Object` so anything that inherits from `Object` (which classes and modules do by default) will be able to use everything in `Kernel`.

However Sorbet's trying to think of scenarios where one could do this:

```
class Example < BasicObject
  include Homebrew
end
```

Now this is obviously something we'll never do but that's where Sorbet is coming from.

This is a complete guess but maybe it's possible to put something like:

```
module Homebrew
  include Kernel
end
```

at the end of `utils.rb` or wherever the best place is. If having the `include Kernel` in one place is possible (I haven't tested), it would be good idea to do so.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 12, 1, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Bo98', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445507596, 'comment_body': "Yeh, this came up in Slack, thanks 👍. I reckon in `global.rb` (if that's enough, hopefully it is).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 12, 5, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 446519969, 'comment_body': 'Can this be done without modifying the code and instead using typing comments?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 27, 12, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 447168416, 'comment_body': "Ah, this is the thing where if you want to use method signatures, `# typed:` sigils have to exist. That's annoying, but there's no way around it.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 29, 18, 27, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 447171880, 'comment_body': 'I wonder if we can use `.rbi` files for this...', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 29, 18, 33, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mistydemeo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 447174943, 'comment_body': "That'd be ideal.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 29, 18, 38, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MikeMcQuaid', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 447183477, 'comment_body': "```suggestion
  sig { params(blk: T.nilable(T.proc.bind(Homebrew::CLI::Parser).void)).returns(Homebrew::CLI::Parser) }
```

because `home_args` is a `Homebrew::CLI::Parser` object (found out with `home_args.class` from the `master` branch because the code doesn't actually run on this branch - I'll get to that in a separate comment!). This gets rid of the following two errors:

```
cmd/home.rb:30: Can not call method parse on void type https://srb.help/7003
    30 |    home_args.parse
            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

cmd/home.rb:30: Can not call method parse on void type https://srb.help/7003
    30 |    home_args.parse
            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 29, 18, 53, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 447186898, 'comment_body': "I feel there are more interesting problems for you to think about right now, but for this PR to be mergeable we will have to rethink how we include Sorbet in Homebrew (as per [your original comment](https://github.com/Homebrew/brew/pull/7725#discussion_r438700311)) - now we're going down the route of method signatures and needing `sorbet-runtime`, `bundle exec srb tc` works, but running the code doesn't.

[{'comment_id': 451091634, 'comment_body': '@issyl0 Without `T.unsafe` we face the following error:
```
utils/git.rb:36: Splats are only supported where the size of the array is known statically https://srb.help/7019
    36 |    out, = Open3.capture3(
    37 |      HOMEBREW_SHIMS_PATH/"scm/git", "-C", repo, "log",
    38 |      "--pretty=format:%h", "--abbrev=7", "--max-count=1",
    39 |      "--diff-filter=d", "--name-only", *args, "--", *files
    40 |    )
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 7, 19, 25, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vidusheeamoli', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451475354, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
  sig { params(repo: Pathname, files: T::Array[Pathname], before_commit: T.nilable(String)).void }
```

`files` seems to be an array of Pathname objects, so we should reflect that.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 8, 11, 36, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451475707, 'comment_body': 'I played with this and you can get rid of the splat here and join the `files` array on spaces, which keeps Sorbet happy (and `brew extract` still works and passes the tests) without having to do `T.unsafe`:

```suggestion
      "--diff-filter=d", "--name-only", *args, "--", files.join(" ")
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 8, 11, 36, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451779285, 'comment_body': 'Unfortunately, I don't think this works. Since we're not operating within a shell, there's no shell to perform splitting, and git itself isn't treating them as multiple files.

Before:

```
# Git.last_revision_commit_of_files("/usr/local/Homebrew", ["LICENSE.txt", "README.md"])
=> ["ac0665d", ["README.md"]]
```

After:

```
# Git.last_revision_commit_of_files("/usr/local/Homebrew", ["LICENSE.txt", "README.md"])
=> [nil, []]
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 8, 19, 33, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mistydemeo', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 451799152, 'comment_body': "This is good - I feel like there was a hypothetical bug here that we've caught!", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 8, 20, 13, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mistydemeo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451801351, 'comment_body': "The original version of the code was structured not only so we didn't have instantiate `User` more than once, but also so that we didn't have to call `Etc.getpwuid` more than once. 😄 How about restructuring this so we just return `@current` if it exists? For example, adding the line

`return @current if defined?(@current)`", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 8, 20, 18, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mistydemeo', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452265790, 'comment_body': "Sorbet does not have a problem with the return type of `@current` but rather the return value of `Etc.getpwuid` (it should never be nil). 

IIUC, `return @current if defined?(@current)` would not solve Sorbet's problem with `Etc.getpwuid`. What do you think?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 14, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vidusheeamoli', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 453004053, 'comment_body': "Sorry, I was unclear. 😄 I'm suggesting doing both. `return @current if defined?(@current)` will ensure that we return the existing object without calling code unnecessarily, but your other change is still needed.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 10, 18, 25, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'mistydemeo', 'type': 'User'}]

-----
We missed one occurrence of the old behaviour of `StringInreplaceExtension` , in `--dry-run` of `brew bump-formula-pr`:

```
$ brew bump-formula-pr torsocks --tag v2.4.0 --revision cec4a733c081e09fb34f0aa4224ffd7b687fb310 -n -w --force
Error: wrong argument type Class (expected Module)
Please report this issue:
  https://docs.brew.sh/Troubleshooting
/usr/local/Homebrew/Library/Homebrew/dev-cmd/bump-formula-pr.rb:449:in `extend'
/usr/local/Homebrew/Library/Homebrew/dev-cmd/bump-formula-pr.rb:449:in `inreplace_pairs'
/usr/local/Homebrew/Library/Homebrew/dev-cmd/bump-formula-pr.rb:296:in `bump_formula_pr'
/usr/local/Homebrew/Library/Homebrew/brew.rb:111:in `<main>'
```

This PR fixes the above usage of `StringInreplaceExtension`

-----
This PR adds a new `brew typecheck` developer command which checks for type errors in the current code with Sorbet.

[{'comment_id': 468192197, 'comment_body': "Now that the Sorbet gems exist for everyone, we don't need this. 🎉", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 21, 19, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468194442, 'comment_body': 'I feel like this could be slightly clearer. I think what you mean is:

> if `args.file` and `args.dir` are both unset, then use `--typed-override` as a default option.

But, from reading the code and it testing for equality, I tried `brew typecheck --file=foo --dir=foo` and got `Error: Options --dir and --file are mutually exclusive.`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 21, 24, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468208691, 'comment_body': "This doesn't appear to work for me?

```
brew typecheck --file=dependencies.rb
[...]
Errors: 13
```

and 

```
brew typecheck --file=./dependencies.rb
[...]
Errors: 15 
```

And those 13 or 15 errors are not all in `dependencies.rb`.

The [Sorbet docs](https://sorbet.org/docs/quickref#run-sorbet-on-a-small-file) say that:

> Note: If there’s a `sorbet/config` file in the current directory, this command will potentially run on more than just this single file. Run `srb tc` from a different folder to check a single file in isolation.

So we might have to do something clever (or 🤢) here?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 10, 21, 56, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'issyl0', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 468209764, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
